    <segment id="1" parent="9" relname="span">
Two design principles that I believe can significantly affect the intuitiveness of an 
interface are mapping and affordance (Preece et al, 2002).</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="1" relname="elaboration">  Mapping with respect to a 
system interface is the relationship between controls and their effect on the system.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="1" relname="elaboration"> 
According to Norman (2002), the movement, placement, and appearance of a control 
should give a visual clue as to what effect that control will have on the system.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="11" relname="condition"> I believe 
that if an interface effectively meets the mapping principle,</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="14" relname="span"> it has a greater probability of 
being considered intuitive by the user.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="1" relname="elaboration"> In addition, Preece et al define the principle of 
affordance as an attribute of an object that allows people to know how to use it.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="13" relname="span"> It seems 
to me that the principle of affordance is closely related to the principle of mapping.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="elaboration"> In 
any event, interfaces that are considered intuitive by their users have probably done a 
good job of meeting the design principles of mapping and affordance. </segment>
